Data Visualization Analysis

Author

Jaeson 戴嘉盛

Published

December 15, 2024

1 Introduction

Data Visualization is a graphical representation of data, for the purpose of uncovering patterns and trends that is not readily apparant in raw data. It serves as a bridge between complex data sets and human understanding, making it easier to analyze and communicate information effectively.

We live in a data-driven word, where efficiency and accessibility is much appreciated in data analysis. By using charts,and graphs learned in data vizualisation, it enables data to be understood faster and make more informed decisions. With effective data visualization, one can highlight correlations, detect outliers, compare variables, and convey findings in a visually engaging and meaningful way.

Tools like R and libraries such as ggplot2 helps us create these wide variety of visualization.

2 Preparation

2.1 Basics Of R Coding

This section will discuss the basics of R as a preparation to create graphs is the following sections.

The basics of R includes using the R packages and using a delimited text data file. One of the primary packages used is ggplot2, which is a cornerstone of data visualization in R.

The ggplot2 package is a R package dedicated for data visualizing. It is renowned for its flexibility, intuitive design, and ability to create elegant, publication-quality plots.

The following is the list of R packages used throughout the document:

library(ggplot2) .
library(gcookbook) 
library(tidyverse)
library(dplyr) 
library(MASS)
library(tidyr)

2.2 Installing a Package

Installing a package extends the functionality of R and allows the access of additional data sets, codes, functions and themes.

Using the install.package() function and write the name of the package, will install the writen package to your device.

install.packages('ggplot2')

To install multiple packages, use install.packages(c()) and write the package names.

install.packages(c('ggplot2', 'gcookbook', 'tidyverse'))

2.3 Loading a Package

Use library() to load a package, that has been installed on your device.

library(ggplot2)
library(gcookbook)

2.4 Updating a Package

To update a package that has already been installed run update.packages()

update.packages(ggplot2)

2.5 Loading a Delimited Text Data file

The most common method for importing data into R is by using a comma-separated values (CSV) file. To do this use read.csv()

data <- read.csv('file.csv')

3 Bar Chart

A Bar chart is used to compare numerical values across different categories, representing them with rectangular bars where length or height reflects the magnitude of the data. Normally, The X-axis of the bar chart represents the position of each bar and the Y-axis represents the height of the bar.

3.1 A Basic Bar Chart

Using the ggplot2 library, the geom_col creates a bar graph

  • Specifying the variable in the X and Y axis will then display the data with bars.

Here is an example using the pg_mean dataset

library(gcookbook) 
pg_mean
  group weight
1  ctrl  5.032
2  trt1  4.661
3  trt2  5.526
  • library(gcookbook): contains the pg_mean dataset
  • pg_mean dataset has two columns: group, weight

Graphing the Bar chart

ggplot(pg_mean, aes(x = group, y = weight)) + 
  geom_col()
  • aes(x = group, y = weight): assigns the variables, in this case X as group and Y as weight
  • geom_col(): Generates bars where the height of each bar represents the Y value for each group.

3.2 Grouping bar chart together

Grouping bar charts together solves the problem of needing to group bars with two variable.

Here is an example using the cabbage_exp dataset

library(gcookbook) 
cabbage_exp
  Cultivar Date Weight        sd  n         se
1      c39  d16   3.18 0.9566144 10 0.30250803
2      c39  d20   2.80 0.2788867 10 0.08819171
3      c39  d21   2.74 0.9834181 10 0.31098410
4      c52  d16   2.26 0.4452215 10 0.14079141
5      c52  d20   3.11 0.7908505 10 0.25008887
6      c52  d21   1.47 0.2110819 10 0.06674995
  • In the cabbage-exp dataset there is two categorical variable which is Cultivar and Date, with one continuous variable weight.

Graphing the bar chart with Cultivar and Date in the x-axis.

ggplot(cabbage_exp, aes(x = Date, y = Weight, fill = Cultivar)) +
  geom_col(position = 'dodge')
  • aes(x = Date, y = Weight, fill = Cultivar): the fill = cultivar assigns colors to distinguish catagories in the cultivar variable
  • position = 'dodge': Adjust the placement of elements such they are position side by side

4 Bar chart with color

4.1 Basic Bar Chart Colors

The simplest way to add colors to a bar chart is by using the fill function, and to add color in the outline use the colour function inside the geom_col

Example using the cabbage_expdataset

ggplot(cabbage_exp, aes(x = Date, y = Weight, fill = Cultivar)) +
  geom_col(colour = 'black',
           position = 'dodge')
  • The color is set as default when using fill
  • geom_col(colour = 'black'): This add colour to the outline

To manually adjust the color, use scale_fill_manual.

ggplot(cabbage_exp, aes(x = Date, y = Weight, fill = Cultivar)) +
  geom_col(colour = 'black',
           position = 'dodge')+
  scale_fill_manual(values = c('lightgreen', 'cornsilk'))
  • scale_fill_manual(values = c('lightgreen', 'cornsilk')): Manually chose the color to add
    • Hex codes are also available, to manually mix the colors (Ex. #FF5733)

4.2 Transparancy Of the Bar Chart

Use alpha to change the transparency of the filled color.

ggplot(cabbage_exp, aes(x = Date, y = Weight, fill = Cultivar)) +
  geom_col(alpha = 0.5,
           position = 'dodge')
  • geom_col(alpha = 0.5): Changes the transparency of the bar graph

4.3 Coloring Negative and Positive Bars

This bar chart shows how to use different colors for positive and negative values.

An example using the climate dataset

head(climate, 5)
    Source Year Anomaly1y Anomaly5y Anomaly10y Unc10y
1 Berkeley 1800        NA        NA     -0.435  0.505
2 Berkeley 1801        NA        NA     -0.453  0.493
3 Berkeley 1802        NA        NA     -0.460  0.486
4 Berkeley 1803        NA        NA     -0.493  0.489
5 Berkeley 1804        NA        NA     -0.536  0.483

In order to color values differently, first we define which values to differentiate

library(dplyr)

Attaching package: 'dplyr'
The following objects are masked from 'package:stats':

    filter, lag
The following objects are masked from 'package:base':

    intersect, setdiff, setequal, union
filtered_climate <- climate %>%
  filter(Source == 'Berkeley' & Year >= 1900) %>%
  mutate(NegorPos = Anomaly10y >= 0)

head(filtered_climate,5)
    Source Year Anomaly1y Anomaly5y Anomaly10y Unc10y NegorPos
1 Berkeley 1900        NA        NA     -0.171  0.108    FALSE
2 Berkeley 1901        NA        NA     -0.162  0.109    FALSE
3 Berkeley 1902        NA        NA     -0.177  0.108    FALSE
4 Berkeley 1903        NA        NA     -0.199  0.104    FALSE
5 Berkeley 1904        NA        NA     -0.223  0.105    FALSE
  • library(dplyr): library for the filter and mutate function
  • filter(Source == 'Berkeley' & Year >= 1900) : filter for only Berkeley and year 1900 and above
  • mutate(NegorPos = Anomaly10y >= 0) : Makes a new column to differentiate between positive and negative

Having negative value and positive value differentiated, simply use fill function to color

ggplot(filtered_climate, aes(x = Year, y = Anomaly10y, fill = NegorPos)) +
  geom_col(position = 'identity')

5 Line chart

A line Chart is used to visualize trends or changes over a continuous variable, typically time, making it ideal for tracking time-series data or analyzing relationships between variables. It is especially effective for identifying trends, comparing categories, or highlighting patterns in data.

5.1 Making a Basic Line Chart

Using the ggplot2 library, the geom_line creates a line graph

Here is an example using the BOD dataset

BOD
  Time demand
1    1    8.3
2    2   10.3
3    3   19.0
4    4   16.0
5    5   15.6
6    7   19.8
  • pg_mean dataset has two columns: Time, demand

Graphing the line chart

ggplot(BOD, aes(x = Time, y = demand)) +
  geom_line()
  • aes(x = Time, y = demand): Assigns Time (X-axis) and demand (Y-axis).
  • geom_line(): Creates a line chart where the X axis is a continuous numeric variable, and Y-axis as a dependent variable.

5.2 Adding Points to a Line graph

geom_point is used to add points to a line graph.

ggplot(BOD, aes(x = Time, y = demand)) +
  geom_line()+
  geom_point()

5.3 Multiple Line, Line Chart

Making a line graph with more than one line

An example using the tg dataset

tg
  supp dose length
1   OJ  0.5  13.23
2   OJ  1.0  22.70
3   OJ  2.0  26.06
4   VC  0.5   7.98
5   VC  1.0  16.77
6   VC  2.0  26.14
  • in addition to dose and length, there is an extra variable supp.

Graphing the line chart

ggplot(tg, aes(x = dose, y = length, colour = supp)) +
  geom_line()
  • aes(x = dose, y = length, colour = supp)): this fuctions allows the extra variable to be differenciated using a different colored line.

5.4 Appearance of Line and Points

Using linetype and ‘Shape’ allows to change the type of lines and point

ggplot(BOD, aes(x = Time, y = demand)) +
  geom_line(linetype = 'dashed', linewidth = 1, colour = 'cornsilk') +
  geom_point(size = 3, shape = 21, fill = 'pink')
  • geom_line(linetype = 'dashed', linewidth = 1, colour = 'cornsilk'):
    • linetype: change the type of line
    • linewidth: change the size of line
    • colour: change the color of the line
  • geom_point(size = 3, shape = 21, fill = 'pink'):
    • size: change the size of point
    • shape: change the type of shape of the point
    • fill: fill the point with chosen color.

6 Histogram

A Histogram is used to visualize the distribution of a continuous numerical variable by grouping data into intervals (bins) and displaying the frequency of observations in each bin. It helps identify patterns such as skewness, modality, or the presence of outliers in the dataset.

6.1 Making Basic Histogram

Using the ggplot2 library, the geom_histogram creates a line graph

Here is an example using the faithful dataset

head(faithful, 5)
  eruptions waiting
1     3.600      79
2     1.800      54
3     3.333      74
4     2.283      62
5     4.533      85
  • faithful dataset has two columns: eruption, waiting. Where it shows a relationship between eruption duration and waiting time

Graphing the Histogram

ggplot(faithful, aes(x = waiting)) +
  geom_histogram()
  • aes(x = waiting): All a histogram needs is a single vector of data. In this case the time as waiting.
  • geom_histogram(): Creates a histogram, where X-axis represents a continuous numeric variable divided into bins, and the Y-axis represents the count of observations within each bin.

6.2 Customizing Histogram

Changing the size of the bin manually.

ggplot(faithful, aes(x = waiting)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 5, fill = 'cornsilk', colour = 'black')
  • geom_histogram(binwidth = 5): The binwidth argument sets the width of each bin to 5 units, meaning the X-axis is divided into bins of equal size, each spanning 5 units.

Calculating the Bin Width Based on the Data Range

bin <- diff(range(faithful$waiting))/15

ggplot(faithful, aes(x = waiting)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = bin, fill = 'cornsilk', colour = 'black')
  • range(faithful$waiting): This calculates the range of the waiting variable
  • diff(): Computes the difference between the maximum and minimum values, giving the total range.
  • geom_histogram(binwidth = bin): Sets the bin width to the calculated value

7 Multigroup Histogram

A multigroup histogram used to compare the distributions of a numerical variable across different levels of a categorical variable. By displaying separate histograms for each group.

Example using the birthwt dataset

library(MASS)
head(birthwt,5)
   low age lwt race smoke ptl ht ui ftv  bwt
85   0  19 182    2     0   0  0  1   0 2523
86   0  33 155    3     0   0  0  0   3 2551
87   0  20 105    1     1   0  0  0   1 2557
88   0  21 108    1     1   0  0  1   2 2594
89   0  18 107    1     1   0  0  1   0 2600
  • The data above shows the non smoker and smoker, on the smoke category, but a problem with multigroup histogram is that the labels for smokers is indicated by 1 and 0. Now we need to label it accordingly

The next example will show how to change label the smoke variable by changing the names of the factor labels

birthwtchanged <- birthwt 
birthwtchanged$smoke <- recode_factor(birthwtchanged$smoke, '0'='No Smoke', '1'= "Smoke")
  • birthwtchanged <- birthwt: making a copy of the old dataset with a new name
  • recode_factor(birthwtchanged$smoke, '0'='No Smoke', '1'= "Smoke"): recodes the value of (0 and 1) with meaningful labels (“No Smoke” and “Smoke”).

Graphing using the modified dataframe

ggplot(birthwtchanged, aes(x = bwt)) +
  geom_histogram(fill = 'cornsilk', colour = 'black') +
  facet_grid(smoke ~ .)
  • ggplot(birthwtchanged): Plotting usind the new data frame
  • facet_grid(smoke ~ .) : Used to create faceted plots to split the data. ## Correlation chart

A correlation chart is a visual representation that shows the relationship between two or more variables.

7.1 Scatter Plots

A scatter plot is used to visualize the relationship between two continuous variables by displaying data points on a two-dimensional graph. It helps identify trends, correlations, and patterns, such as linear, nonlinear, or no correlation between the variables.

Using the ggplot2 library, the geom_point creates a density graph

Here is an example using the heightweight dataset

head(heightweight, 5)
  sex ageYear ageMonth heightIn weightLb
1   f   11.92      143     56.3     85.0
2   f   12.92      155     62.3    105.0
3   f   12.75      153     63.3    108.0
4   f   13.42      161     59.0     92.0
5   f   15.92      191     62.5    112.5
  • heightweight dataset, which includes information about individuals’ age (ageYear), height (heightIn)

Graphing the scatter plot

ggplot(heightweight, aes(x = ageYear, y = heightIn)) +
  geom_point()
  • aes(x = ageYear, y = heightIn): maps the ageYear variable to the X-axis, and the heightIn variable to the Y-axis.
  • geom_point(): adds a scatter plot layer, plotting individual data points to visualize the relationship between age and height.

8 Correlation chart: Color by group

8.1 Grouping Points by color or shape

This helps group variables to shape or color.

Here is an example using the heightweight dataset

head(heightweight, 5)
  sex ageYear ageMonth heightIn weightLb
1   f   11.92      143     56.3     85.0
2   f   12.92      155     62.3    105.0
3   f   12.75      153     63.3    108.0
4   f   13.42      161     59.0     92.0
5   f   15.92      191     62.5    112.5
  • heightweight dataset, which includes information about individuals’ age (ageYear), height (heightIn)

Plotting scatter plot with manually chosen color and shape

ggplot(heightweight, aes(x = ageYear, y = heightIn, shape = sex, colour = sex)) +
  geom_point() +
  scale_shape_manual(values = c(1,2)) +
  scale_colour_manual(values = c("m" = "blue", "f" = "red"))
  • aes(shape = sex, colour = sex): Categorize gender m and f with color and shape
  • scale_shape_manual(values = c(1,2)): Manually change the shape of gender
  • scale_colour_manual(values = c("m" = "blue", "f" = "red")): manually change the color of gender

9 Density chart

A density chart visualizes the distribution of a continuous variable as a smooth curve, highlighting patterns like peaks and spread.

9.1 Making a Basic Density Chart

Using the ggplot2 library, the geom_density creates a density graph

Here is an example using the faithful dataset

head(faithful, 5)
  eruptions waiting
1     3.600      79
2     1.800      54
3     3.333      74
4     2.283      62
5     4.533      85
  • faithful dataset has two columns: eruption, waiting. Where it shows a relationship between eruption duration and waiting time

Graphing the density chart

ggplot(faithful, aes(x = waiting)) +
  geom_density()
  • aes(x = waiting): Maps the waiting variable to the X-axis. The density will be calculated based on this variable.
  • geom_density(): The density plot visualizes the distribution of the waiting variable as a smooth curve

9.2 Multiple Density Chart

This allows for dencity curves with multiple groups of data

Example of this is plotted using birthwt dataset

head(birthwt, 5)
   low age lwt race smoke ptl ht ui ftv  bwt

First we need to modify the dataset to convert the smoke variable as a nameable factor.

birthwtsmoke <- birthwt %>%
  mutate(smoke = as.factor(smoke))
  • birthwtsmoke <- birthwt %>%: Copying the orginal dataset and renaming it to modify.

Plotting the multiple Density chart with different colors

ggplot(birthwtsmoke, aes(x = bwt, fill = smoke)) +
  geom_density(alpha = .3)

10 Boxplot

A box plot is used to summarize the distribution of a continuous variable, showing its median, quartiles, and potential outliers. It helps compare distributions across different groups and identify variations or anomalies in the data.

10.1 Creating a Basic Box plot

Using the ggplot2 library, the geom_boxplot creates a boxplot graph

Here is an example using the birthwt dataset

head(birthwt, 5)
   low age lwt race smoke ptl ht ui ftv  bwt
85   0  19 182    2     0   0  0  1   0 2523
86   0  33 155    3     0   0  0  0   3 2551
87   0  20 105    1     1   0  0  0   1 2557
88   0  21 108    1     1   0  0  1   2 2594
89   0  18 107    1     1   0  0  1   0 2600
  • The two varibale used for the boxplot from the birthwt data set are:
    • bwt: Represents birth weight (the variable of interest for the box plot).
    • race: Represents the race category of the mother (used for grouping in the plot).

Graphing the box plot

ggplot(birthwt, aes(x = factor(race), y = bwt)) +
  geom_boxplot()

  • aes(x = factor(race), y = bwt): maps race to the X-axis as categorical groups and bwt to the Y-axis.

  • geom_boxplot():

    • Adds box plots to show the distribution of bwt for each race group.
    • The box shows the interquartile range, the line represents the median, and whiskers show the data range within 1.5 times the IQR. Outliers are displayed as dots.

10.2 Adding notches

Notches in a box plot represent a confidence interval around the median, helping to assess the variability of the median value.

Example

ggplot(birthwt, aes(x = factor(race), y = bwt)) +
  geom_boxplot(notch = TRUE)
  • geom_boxplot(notch = TRUE): Adds notches to boxplots

11 Additional Universal Functions

11.1 Modifying label in the plot

Use labs() function to modify labels in the plot

ggplot(cabbage_exp, aes(x = Date, y = Weight, fill = Cultivar)) +
  labs(title='Cabbage Experiment',
       x = 'Date', 
       y = 'Cabbage Weight (kg)',
       fill = 'Variety of Cabbage',
       caption = 'By Jaeson, Data Vizualization Course, Tunghai University, 2024')+
  geom_col(position = 'dodge')
  • labs(): This function is used to modify the labels in the plot.
    • title: Sets the plot title.
    • x: Sets the label for the X-axis.
    • y: Sets the label for the Y-axis.
    • fill: Change the legend title.
    • caption: adds a caption label.

11.2 Changing the overall appearance

Use theme() function to change the overall appearance

ggplot(cabbage_exp, aes(x = Date, y = Weight, fill = Cultivar)) +
  labs(title='Cabbage Experiment',
       x = 'Date', 
       y = 'Cabbage Weight (kg)',
       fill = 'Variety of Cabbage',
       caption = 'By Jaeson, Data Vizualization Course, Tunghai University, 2024')+
  geom_col(position = 'dodge')+
  theme(legend.position= "bottom", 
        axis.title.x = element_text(size = 12), 
        axis.title.y = element_text(size = 12),
        plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, size=20))
  • theme(): This function modifies the overall appearance of the plot.
    • legend.position: Moves the legend to the top of the plot. Use none to remove legend.
    • plot.title: Customizes the title’s appearance.
      • hjust: to position the title
    • axis.title.x and axis.title.y: Customize the size of the axis titles.

11.3 Using predefined themes

There are 7 predefined themes in ggplot library, which are: theme_gray(),theme_bw(), theme_linedraw(), theme_light(), theme_minimal(), theme_classic(), theme_dark(), theme_void().

ggplot(cabbage_exp, aes(x = Date, y = Weight, fill = Cultivar)) +
  geom_col(position = 'dodge')+
  theme_classic()
  • theme_classic(): using one of the predefined themes
